/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

posts.com: Anyone here ever sold their plasma? How much did you make? Any tips? I'm skellymode so I feel like it would knock me out for a whole weekend.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I have. I will walk you through what I remember, it was a shitload of rules.


The payments are weird, I was able to donate once every 5 days, 5 times max a month. You get a first time physical that they pay you $15 for, then the next day if all your tests were fine then first time was $30, then $25 then $20 then $15 for the last two times. If you have a gap of 14 days from your last donation, the rate would reset to $30. If you didn't wait 14 days, in the new month your first donation started at $25 and then the next donation was $20 and the last 3 were $15.

You cannot donate plasma if you do not pass the physical, but you keep the initial $15 no matter what. Your donations get tested (they take some from the top and test it as you do the donation since it takes like 30 minutes to donate) and you can get a few types of suspensions that mean different things. If your plasma levels were too low or somehow messed up, you got $10 for the donation even though they threw it out and you got either a blue suspension (which means you can't donate for 14 days) or a yellow suspension (which would require a 30 day wait and then you'd need to get a physical that you'd get paid $15 for doing). If you test positive for an STD from your blood that isn't a permanent disease or some other random issues (I can't remember the list, but they aren't all STDs), you got a red suspension meaning you can't donate plasma for a year and you have to get the blood tests before donating every time you donate from then on(meaning a 30 minute wait before getting to donate). If your blood comes back HIV positive or that you have a blood disease or something then you get a black suspension meaning you can donate plasma ever again.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>71897506
Another thing I remember is they do a casual physical every time, so they take your weight and check your arms, take a heart rate, blood pressure and blood oxygen right before they get you into the machine. If it's slow, you can check in and get in a machine in a couple of minutes after walking in the door, but normally you wait 10-30 minutes and the donation takes 30 minutes, so I planned for an hour.

They give you a snack and a juice you have to finish before you leave, but it takes like 30 seconds to get down.

The machines were close enough that you could easily speak with people while you were donating with and I got a couple dates from that place (I was in college in a college town so it was mostly just college students donating, not extremely poor people).

If you turn out to be squeamish about donating, and have a panic attack or pass out from a non-medical reason, you would usually get a blue suspension or they would advise you to stop coming if it happened a few times. I had a roommate that came with me and ended up crying and having a panic attack then he passed out, it was so fucking funny.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
As for tips, don't plan on going to class or work after donating, you get foggy headed for a good 3-6 hours afterwards. I advise getting lunch or dinner afterwards and eating slowly then taking a nap, cuts the foggy headedness by alot and you recover better.

Some people can't get hard for the rest of the day after donating, I could but I was never horny until the foggy headed feeling wore off.

The next few days you might get some muscle weakness or low energy, but usually you're totally fine after that initial foggy head business. I would exercise fine the day after with no issues. I knew some guys that would be sick in bed for a day after donating, but this guy was fat. Donating plasma uses machines that return your blood platelets back to your body and only take the plasma, so it isn't as severe as blood donation.

>what about Alice do you love so darn much?
There is not a single thing that I do not love. Alice in her totality is the only girl I could ever pour the sweetest notes of my heart for. But to not escape your question I will name several things.
Her seemingly pessimistic tone, in which she can so effortlessly sneak some existential undertones, makes me think of long night walks together under the Moon during which we would discuss meaninglessness of life and how to overcome it.
I truly admire her artistic and surreal Wonderland that she was able to create inside her head, as it was the main thing that drawn me to her game. I could listen to this mad girl passionately talk about her Wonderland for hours and never have enough.
Her perseverance to march despite the terrible events that she had to go through. That mixed with her relying pretty much only on herself.
Her search for hurtful truth instead of living a life of delusion is what stops me from believing that she is real or she loves me. It would be a dishonour to what her story preaches.
Also that animal remains appear poignant to her. That she likes rabbits. That she has some interest in Greek mythology. That her dresses look fantastic.
I do not know many things about her still but every time I learn something knew about her, or hear her creator talk about her, it feels like I already know that and her image of who she truly is to me is never disrupted.
And her physical beauty is a significant part of my obsession with her too, of course. That perfect face of hers still visits my dreams and I cannot have enough of looking at her. When I see her, I want to remain faithful and loyal to her for decades. Even centuries or eternity, if that was within my power. She is always the most beautiful to me. No matter how many years pass.

I had a "career" in the past. I was TIG welding parts for medical equipment like MRI machines at a very successful company. Things I was welding were being used in hospitals.
It sucked. I realized that unless you LOVE your career, your soul will be crushed very early on. I don't care for welding, so the monotony of doing it 50+ hours a week got old very fast.
I got fired because I refused to do overtime one weekend...one weekend. My employer told me that they expect welders to be welders, and welders love to weld. I told him I don't, I just do it for money and if I had it my way I would never do overtime. He fired me on the spot. They replaced me with my friend who is also a welder and genuinely loves it, he's happy to work 50+ hours a week. He loves it. He also has adhd and is covered in Rick and Morty tattoos.
I also dislike how these career jobs almost always feel like High School. The office culture is very similar to High School.
so nope, not for me. I'm much happier with my current arrangement. 25 hours a week, small business so we only have myself + 4 other employees, no micromanaging, no drama. It feels way more natural.

No more than 3 days and 30 hours in a week. I spent most of my 20s working 60-72 hour weeks and I feel cheated out of more or less a decade of my life. I now have health problems that people normally get in their 50s and 60s and a fatty liver from overwork induced alcoholism. I also have various issues from using cocaine and Adderall to deal with exhaustion and lost sleep. Having a couple million in combined savings and owning a house doesn't make the consequences of working yourself to death any better.

Also, never work a job with productivity rates. If a company implements them, quit on the spot. They'll start low and get raised until only the top 20% remains. Then, you'll work constant mandatory OT because new hires will quit in their first three months. Finally they'll start using temps who don't have rate, but you'll still be on mandatory OT forever because you will be 3-5 times as productive, so it makes good business sense even if you make double what the temps do. And in the end, I was fired because I couldn't make rate after getting clean.

Bosses are mostly inhuman villains. Very few of them could or would do what they expect you to. You are a depreciating asset to them, not a person.
